        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/r/bbce88/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2024-09-17T04:12:47.249Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Similar to how the iOS Signal app has VoiceOver actions to be used, it would be beneficial to have a similar user experience for having TalkBack, the screen reader on Android, to have the “Accessibility Actions” incorporated in the message history. Actions for editing a message, copying text, deleting, and related features for messages would be welcomed.</p>\n<p>Currently, a user of the Signal app has to perform a double tap and hold gesture to access actions for a particular message. On the iOS app, a user has to only locate a message, and flick up with one finger to access the actions that are exposed to VoiceOver.</p>\n<p>Android has a similar feature, called Accessibility Actions. It is documented here:</p>\n<p><a>https://developer.android.com/guide/topics/ui/accessibility/principles#accessibility-actions</a></p>\n<p>This would eliminate the need to double tap and hold to access the context menu for a message when TalkBack is running, in an ideal implementation. It would allow the user to just access the menu of available actions for a message in a simplified manner.</p>",
